(290,'*<u>\'\'\'Install and configure Elasticsearch\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>\nDownload Elasticsearch\nwget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/elasticsearch/elasticsearch-7.13.2-x86_64.rpm\nyum localinstall elasticsearch-7.13.2-x86_64.rpm -y </pre>\n\n*<u>\'\'\'Configure Elasticsearch\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>Edit configuration file with respective parameters:\n/etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml</pre>\n\n*<u>\'\'\'X-Pack Security\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>In default settings, X-Pack security is disable. To enable this, followings are the steps.\n* Create SSL certificate for Elasticsearch and enable SSL\n# cd /etc/elasticsearch/\n# /usr/share/elasticsearch/bin/elasticsearch-certutil ca</pre>\n<pre>Press Enter for all (With blank password for certificate)</pre>\n\n[[File:Ca-certs.png|frame|none]]\n\n[[File:Certs.png|frame|none]]\n\n[[File:Complete-certs.png|frame|none]]\n\n*<u>\'\'\'Update elasticsearch.yml\'\'\'</u>\n[[File:A2.png|frame|none]]\n*<u>\'\'\'Generate elasticsearch credentials\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>#/usr/share/elasticsearch/bin/elasticsearch-setup-passwords auto\nCopy all credentials.</pre>\n\n*<u>\'\'\'Start Elasticsearch\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>systemctl start elasticsearch\nElasticsearch will start in default port 9200</pre>\n\n*<u>\'\'\'Install and configure Kibana\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>#wget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/kibana/kibana-7.2.0-x86_64.rpm\nyum localinstall kibana-7.2.0-x86_64.rpm -y</pre>\n<pre>Configure Kibana:\nEdit kibana.yaml with elasticsearch credentials</pre>\n[[File:Kibana.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>Kibana Dashboard will be served in default port 5601\nUsing proxy we can configure it in different port and domain.\nPlease check nginx configuration for details.\nHere we have configured Kibana Dashboard in\nhttps://rrlogmonitor.ril.com/\n</pre>\n\n*<u>\'\'\'Install Grafana Server\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>\nFor Retail IT, Grafana & Kibana server is installed in 10.129.36.230\n\nDownload Grafana server:\nwget https://dl.grafana.com/oss/release/grafana-8.0.3-1.x86_64.rpm\nyum localinstall grafana-8.0.3-1.x86_64.rpm -y\n</pre>\n*<u>\'\'\'Configure Grafana Server\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>\nEdit file with specified parameters:\n/etc/grafana/grafana.ini\n\nIf you are using proxy server to access Grafana Dashboard, need to configure root_url as\nroot_url = %(protocol)s://%(domain)s:%(http_port)s/grafana/\n</pre>\n*<u>\'\'\'Start Grafana Server\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>\nsystemctl start grafana-server\n\nNow Grafana Dashboard is accessible via default port number 3000.\nIf you configured proxy, then can be accessible as https://<domain.com>/grafana/\nFor Retail IT UI is https://rrlogmonitor.ril.com/grafana/\n</pre>\n\n== Log Monitoring ==\n*<u>\'\'\'Logstash\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>For log monitoring in Kibana or Grafana, we need to install and configure Logstash in Application Server</pre>\n<pre>Download and Install Logstash:\nwget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/logstash/logstash-7.4.0.rpm\nyum localinstall logstash-7.4.0.rpm -y</pre>\n<pre>In Windows, download and extract binary(zip) in C:\\Logstash\\</pre>\n<pre>Configure logstash:\nThere is multiple ways to configure logstash. Here we are using pipelines for multiple log analysis.\nLogstash configuration files are inside ./config\nFirst create a new directory in ./config/conf.d, here we will create separate config files for each application logs.\nFor example:\nCreate a new file ./config/conf.d/newerr.conf\n</pre>\n[[File:Log.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>\nIn the filter section, we can configure different filters as per requirements.\nFilter Example:\n------------\nfilter {\n	grok {\n		match => { \"message\" => \"%{DATA}%{LOGLEVEL:([ERR]?(?:OR)?|[C|c]rit?(?:ical)?|CRIT?(?:ICAL)?)}\\s*%{GREEDYDATA:logMessage}\"}\n	}\n}\n------------</pre>\n<pre>Now create a pipeline by editing ./config/pipelines.yml\nExample:</pre>\n[[File:Pipeline.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>We can create multiple pipeline in same yaml file</pre>\n<u>\'\'\'Start Logstash service\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>systemctl start logstash</pre>\n\n== Create Index Pattern ==\n<u>\'\'\'Create a Pattern in Kibana\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>Login Kibana UI with credentials:\nExpand management, select Index Pattern, and Click on \"Create index pattern\"</pre>\n[[File:Kibana Index.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>Follow the steps as bellow</pre>\n[[File:Kibana2.png|frame|none]]\n\n<u>\'\'\'Now time to explore logs in Kibana / Grafana\'\'\'</u>\n\n\'\'\'Kibana:\'\'\'\n<pre>Click on Discover:\nSelect the Index Pattern \"otperror-*\"\nYou will get the logs in the Dashboard</pre>\n\n\'\'\'Grafana:\'\'\'\n<pre>Open the Grafana URL and login with credentials:\nSelect Configuration and click on \"Data Sources\"\n[[File:G1.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>There are multiple data sources for Grafana\nYou can search it by typing, e.g. elastic\nNow select the Elasticsearch</pre>\n[[File:G2.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>Fill the form with respective parameters and save.</pre>\n[[File:G3.png|frame|none]]\n\n<pre>Click on Explore\nSelect Elasticsearch and make the qurey.\nIt will show the logs in the Grafana UI as bellow</pre>\n[[File:E1.png|frame|none]]\n== Dashboard and Alerting ==\n*\'\'\'<u>Grafana Dashboard\'\'\'</u>\n<pre>Click on + sign to create a Dashboard\nAnd follow the steps to complete.\nSet the query as per requirement.</pre>\n[[File:1.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>For correct query, graph will be displayed in the Dashboard</pre>\n[[File:2.png|frame|none]]\n\n\'\'\'<u>Alerting:</u>\'\'\'\n<pre>Grafana Alert is configured based on Dashboard Query.\nPlease note, only graph visualization support alert, so do not select any other visualization.\nFor Alerting on specific queries, first, need to configure a notification channel. Channel may be different types like Email, Slack, Telegram etc. We are here currently configuring Email Channel. For Email setting, deployed server should able to send mail through SMTP.</pre>\n[[File:3.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>Configure grafana.ini for SMTP relay</pre>\n[[File:Ini.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>Now create a channel by filling up the form with respective parameters</pre>\n[[File:Channel.png|frame|none]]\n\n\'\'\'Alert Rules\'\'\'\n<pre>Alert rules are conditions, on which notification are sent. To create rules, edit the dashboard panel and choose the Alert tab</pre>\n[[File:Alert.png|none]]\n<pre>Test rule and Save\nRules can be paused or resume</pre>','utf-8'),
