(316,'*\'\'\'Configmap is used for feeding application configuration or properties\'\'\'\n<pre>Elastration is bellow with examples</pre>\n<pre>Configmap can be configured in multiple ways. Here we will discuss volume mount with key and without key</pre>\n*\'\'\'1. <u>Volume Mount with a key</u>\'\'\'\n<pre>For example, in a Maven application, normally we have defined configurations in a properties file, i.e. application.properties. We can make a ConfigMap with this file and feed it to the container at run time.\nNow Create the ConfigMap:\n\nkubectl -n <NameSpace> create configmap <ConfigMap_Name> --from-file=<ConfigMap_Key>=<File_Path>\nkubectl -n kube-rdip create configmap application-config --from-file=application.properties=/path/to/application.properties\n\nThis will create a ConfigMap name=application-config and Key=application.properties</pre>\n<pre>Next we will make the block in YAML file to feed this ConfigMap\nWe will use this ConfigMap as a file inside the container and the file will feed in Maven application.\n\nIn the container section of the YAML, we have to modify the args as:\n----\nargs: [\"java -Dspring.config.additional-location=/config/application.properties -jar application.jar]\n----\n----\n        volumeMounts:\n        - name: Release.DefinitionName\n          mountPath: \"/config\"\n          readOnly: true\n----\n----\n      volumes:\n      - name: application_name\n        configMap:\n          name: application_name\n          items:\n          - key: application.properties\n            path: application.properties</pre>\n\n*\'\'\'2. <u>ConfigMap without a key</u>\n<pre>Create the ConfigMap\nkubectl -n kube-rdip create configmap service-config --from-file=/path/to/service-file\nRespective block in YAML will be\n----\n        - name: service-config\n          mountPath: /etc/services\n          subPath: services\n          readOnly: true\n----\n      - name: service-config\n        configMap:\n          name: service-config','utf-8'),
