(322,'*\'\'\'Kubernetes Secrets\'\'\'\n<pre>A Secret is an object that contains a small amount of sensitive data such as a password, a token, or a key. Such information might otherwise be put in a Pod specification or in a container image. Using a Secret means that you don\'t need to include confidential data in your application code.</pre>\n<pre>Secrets are similar to ConfigMaps but are specifically intended to hold confidential data.</pre>\n<pre>\nWe can create a secret as:\nkubectl create secret generic empty-secret\n\nCheck this secret as:\nkubectl get secret empty-secret\nor\nkubectl get secret empty-secret -o yaml\n</pre>\n<pre>A secret can be created with multiple key-value pairs.</pre>\n[[File:Secrets.png|frame|none]]\n<pre>Keys can be refered by Variables put in application.properties or any other configuration files.\n\nFor example:\ndigital.api.platform.app.sap.connector.rfc.config.user=${SAPUSER}\ndigital.api.platform.app.sap.connector.rfc.config.password=${SAPPASS}\n\nThese value parts are feed by respective Keys in the YAML as:\n....\n.....\n        env:\n        - name: SAPUSER\n          valueFrom:\n            secretKeyRef:\n              name: my-secret\n              key: sap.key.user\n        - name: SAPPASS\n          valueFrom:\n            secretKeyRef:\n              name: my-secret\n              key: sap.key.pass\n.....\n....\n</pre>\n\'\'\'Note:\'\'\' Kubernetes Secrets are, by default, stored unencrypted in the API server\'s underlying data store (etcd). Anyone with API access can retrieve or modify a Secret, and so can anyone with access to etcd.','utf-8'),
